abla \] 13.1.1 Adjusted means Where the lines cross at the centered X level of 0 are the adjusted means. That is, they are the predicted scores for the treatments at the “average” value of the uncentered covariate. Based on this additive model, we obtain the following adjusted means. \[ i=1,\ldots , r-1:\quad \hat{\mu}_i = \hat{\mu}_{ ullet} +\hat{	au}_i \qquad \hat{\mu}_r=\hat{\mu}_{ ullet} -\sum_{i=1}^{r-1}\hat{	au}_i \] The goal is to typically compare the adjusted means, as would be done for the 1-Way ANOVA. The standard errors depend on the variance-covariance matrix of the regression coefficients, which is obtained with the vcov function from the regression model fit. The variance-covariance matrix for this example is given below. \[  egin{bmatrix} \hat{V}\left\{\hat{\mu}_{ ullet}ight\} &amp; \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{\mu}_{ ullet},\hat{	au}_1ight\} &amp; \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{\mu}_{ ullet},\hat{	au}_2ight\} &amp; \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{\mu}_{ ullet},\hat{\gamma}ight\} \ \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{\mu}_{ ullet},\hat{	au}_1ight\} &amp; \hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_1ight\} &amp; \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_1,\hat{	au}_2ight\} &amp; \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_1,\hat{\gamma}ight\} \ \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{\mu}_{ ullet},\hat{	au}_2ight\} &amp; \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_1,\hat{	au}_2ight\} &amp; \hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_2ight\} &amp; \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_2,\hat{\gamma}ight\} \ \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{\mu}_{ ullet},\hat{\gamma}ight\} &amp; \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_1,\hat{\gamma}ight\} &amp; \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_2,\hat{\gamma}ight\} &amp; \hat{V}\left\{\hat{\gamma}ight\} \end{bmatrix} \] \[ i,i&#39; &lt; r \quad \hat{SE}\left\{\hat{	au}_i-\hat{	au}_{i&#39;}ight\} = \sqrt{\hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_iight\}+\hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_{i&#39;}ight\} -2\hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_i,\hat{	au}_{i&#39;}ight\}} \] When comparing the first \(r-1\) treatments with the \(r^{th}\), we use the following result. \[ \hat{	au}_i-\hat{	au}_r=\hat{	au}_i-\left(-\sum_{i=1}^{r-1}\hat{	au}_iight)= 2\hat{	au}_i + \sum_{\stackrel{i&#39;=1}{i&#39;
e i}}^{r-1}\hat{	au}_{i&#39;} \] Then the (messy) standard errors for these differences are as follow. \[ \hat{SE}\left\{\hat{	au}_i-\hat{	au}_right\} = \sqrt{4\hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_iight\} + \sum_{\stackrel{i&#39;=1}{i&#39;
e i}}^{r-1}\hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_{i&#39;}ight\} +4\sum_{\stackrel{i&#39;=1}{i&#39;
e i}}^{r-1}\hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_i,\hat{	au}_{i&#39;}ight\} +2\sum_{\stackrel{i&#39;=1}{i&#39;
e i}}^{r-2}\sum_{\stackrel{i&#39;&#39;=i&#39;+1}{i&#39;&#39;
e i}}^{r-1} \hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_{i&#39;},\hat{	au}_{i&#39;&#39;}ight\} } \] Here, we consider a few cases to observe these variance calculations. When \(r=2\), we have the following simple case. \[ \hat{	au}_2 = -\hat{	au}_1 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \hat{	au}_1-\hat{	au}_2= 2\hat{	au}_1 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_1-\hat{	au}_2ight\} =4\hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_1ight\} \] When \(r=3\), as in the skin softener study, we have the following results. \[ \hat{	au}_3 = -\hat{	au}_1-\hat{	au}_2 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \hat{	au}_1-\hat{	au}_3 = \hat{	au}_1-\left[\hat{	au}_1-\hat{	au}_2ight]= 2\hat{	au}_1+\hat{	au}_2 \] \[\quad \Rightarrow \quad \hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_1-\hat{	au}_3ight\}= 4\hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_1ight\}+\hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_2ight\}+ 4\hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_1,\hat{	au}_2ight\} \] Finally, when \(r=4\), have the following results. \[ \hat{	au}_1-\hat{	au}_4 = \hat{	au}_1-\left[\hat{	au}_1-\hat{	au}_2-\hat{	au}_3ight]= 2\hat{	au}_1+\hat{	au}_2+\hat{	au}_3 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \] \[ \hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_1-\hat{	au}_4ight\}= 4\hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_1ight\}+\hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_2ight\}+ \hat{V}\left\{\hat{	au}_3ight\}+ 4\hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_1,\hat{	au}_2ight\}+ 4\hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_1,\hat{	au}_3ight\}+ 2\hat{\mbox{COV}}\left\{\hat{	au}_2,\hat{	au}_3ight\} \] Example 13.2 - Comparison of Skin Softeners We obtain the adjusted means and their differences along with multiple comparisons with the following R code. dsm &lt;- read.csv(&quot;data/deadseaminerals.csv&quot;) head(dsm,2); tail(dsm,2) ## trt_Grp pre_x post_y gel gelDS ## 1 1 121.1 76.3 1 0 ## 2 1 375.4 265.1 1 0 ## trt_Grp pre_x post_y gel gelDS ## 59 3 138.59 107.22 0 0 ## 60 3 134.89 125.20 0 0 dsm$I1 &lt;- ifelse(dsm$trt_Grp==1,1,ifelse(dsm$trt_Grp==3,-1,0)) dsm$I2 &lt;- ifelse(dsm$trt_Grp==2,1,ifelse(dsm$trt_Grp==3,-1,0)) dsm$Xc &lt;- dsm$pre_x - mean(dsm$pre_x) dsm.mod1 &lt;- lm(post_y ~ I1 + I2 + Xc, data=dsm